To sweeten the deal I will even throw in a few boxes of ammo as well !!!!The new clarification of opinion on Pistol braces was published in an open letter this year, and the letter states, “an NFA firearm has not necessarily been made when the device is not reconfigured for use as a shoulder stock – even if the attached firearm happens to be fired from the shoulder. To the extent that the January 2015 Open Letter implied or has been construed to hold that incidental, sporadic, or situational “use” of an arm-brace (in its original approved configuration) equipped firearm from a firing position at or near the shoulder was sufficient to constitute “redesign,” such interpretations are incorrect and not consistent with ATF’s interpretation of the statute or the manner in which it has historically been enforced.”. In other words, if the brace is unaltered and you happen to fire it from the shoulder on occasion you have not made the AR pistol and NFA Short barrel rifle. This awesome build is the third of this type I have put together and sold. Once you get this in your hands you are going to love it! title: For Sale/Trade:  Pre-WWI French Mod. 1882 Infantry Officer Sword
postcontent: This is an exceptional example of a pre-WWI Model 1882 French Infantry officer pattern saber. This one, however, is unique in that it was not arsenal produced and was ordered directly from renown swordsmiths F. Delecour & Bakes of Paris. The backstrap of the hilt was custom engraved with the monogram cypher of its owner, initials “J.R.” who would have been of some means financially, possibly of French nobility. The sword bears the FBD seal of F. Delecour and Bakes on the ricasso as well as being signed F.D.Bakes on the guard just below the ricasso. The sword remains in the unsharpened state it was received from the maker which is very uncommon to find. The braided brass wire on the walnut grip also remains intact.Ford additional pictures, check it out on gunbroker:https://www.gunbroker.com/item/739640228
